WEBVTT

00:02.850 --> 00:08.839
you're listening to a teaching from Reality LA.

00:08.859 --> 00:10.502
We're in a series right now on the Book of Acts.

00:11.203 --> 00:14.688
This is the story of the movement of the early church throughout the Roman Empire.

00:14.708 --> 00:18.454
We want to see the same thing happening right here in Los Angeles.

00:18.955 --> 00:24.203
And today we're looking at Acts 16, talking about how to plant a church in a pagan city.

00:25.846 --> 00:31.314
So imagine with me for a minute that you go into a new big city and quickly realize

00:31.458 --> 00:35.002
that there is not one Christian in the entire city.

00:35.642 --> 00:37.464
And you're a follower of Jesus.

00:37.545 --> 00:39.627
You want to be faithful to the Lord there.

00:39.687 --> 00:41.629
You know that you need Christian community.

00:41.669 --> 00:42.710
What do you do?

00:42.790 --> 00:45.673
How would you introduce people to Jesus?

00:45.753 --> 00:48.596
Would it even be possible to start a church there?

00:49.537 --> 00:53.722
Well, in Acts chapter 16, that's exactly what Paul and Silas do.

00:54.262 --> 00:57.686
They go to a city called Philippi to plant a church.

00:58.367 --> 01:01.330
And Philippi was a Roman city in Greece.

01:01.922 --> 01:05.647
And it was urban, pluralistic, and utterly pagan.

01:06.288 --> 01:09.893
They lived their lives to the glory of Greek and Roman gods.

01:09.914 --> 01:13.959
They spent their time in theaters and gyms and learning the latest theories.

01:14.240 --> 01:19.167
They followed their desires, and none of them had ever heard about Jesus.

01:20.008 --> 01:25.216
And so, Philippi is very different than where we began in the book of Acts in Jerusalem.

01:25.997 --> 01:26.898
Philippi

01:26.978 --> 01:28.984
There are zero followers of Jesus.

01:29.044 --> 01:30.830
There are hardly any Jews there.

01:30.890 --> 01:32.415
There's no synagogue.

01:32.916 --> 01:36.166
They live there with their ultimate loyalty to Caesar.

01:36.206 --> 01:41.362
And yet, Paul and Silas are going there to plant a church.

01:41.698 --> 01:45.943
Now, obviously, Los Angeles is not a city with zero Christians.

01:46.383 --> 01:53.091
I'm so grateful for the many churches in our city and for the generations of believers who have gone before us in this city.

01:53.772 --> 01:58.357
But in a lot of ways, Los Angeles feels more like Philippi than Jerusalem.

01:58.838 --> 02:05.746
This is a global city, an urban, pluralistic, power-centered city, a city shaped by image,

02:06.306 --> 02:09.070
influence, desire, money, and status.

02:09.772 --> 02:16.182
A city where loyalty is not expressed to Caesar, but to career, platform, self-expression, or politics.

02:16.903 --> 02:19.747
And it's a city where people aren't asking, how can I follow Jesus?

02:19.788 --> 02:22.231
They're asking, how can I build my life?

02:23.273 --> 02:29.623
And increasingly, most people in Los Angeles genuinely don't know anything about Christianity.

02:30.344 --> 02:31.346
And so here we are.

02:31.650 --> 02:42.104
a church that was planted 20 years ago, planted by brave men and women who pioneered and sacrificially moved into the heart of the city proclaiming the good news of Jesus.

02:42.665 --> 02:45.329
And by God's grace, 20 years later, we're still here.

02:45.349 --> 02:54.041
And so this passage is going to teach us not only how to plant a church in a pagan city, but how to thrive as a church in a pagan city.

02:54.682 --> 02:58.347
So let me read this passage for us and then I'll open our time with a word of prayer.

02:58.907 --> 03:00.850
It's Acts chapter 16,

03:01.314 --> 03:03.057
verses 11 through 40.

03:03.638 --> 03:07.344
Acts chapter 16 starting in verse 11.

03:09.188 --> 03:22.010
So, setting sail from Troas, we made a direct voyage to Sumothrace and the following day to Neapolis and from there to Philippi, which is a leading city of the district of Macedonia and a Roman colony.

03:22.751 --> 03:24.594
We remained in this city some days

03:24.738 --> 03:33.030
And on the Sabbath day, we went outside the gate to the riverside where we suppose there was a place of prayer and we sat down and spoke to the women who had come together.

03:33.972 --> 03:40.862
One who heard us was a woman named Lydia from the city of Thyatira, a seller of purple goods who was a worshipper of God.

03:41.763 --> 03:45.329
The Lord opened her heart to pay attention to what was said by Paul.

03:46.210 --> 03:54.162
And after she was baptized and her household as well, she urged us saying, if you have judged me to be faithful to the Lord, come to my house and stay.

03:54.370 --> 03:55.591
and she prevailed upon us.

03:56.793 --> 04:05.403
As we were going to the place of prayer, we were met by a slave girl who had a spirit of divination and brought her owners much gain by fortune telling.

04:06.104 --> 04:13.113
She followed Paul and us crying out, these men are servants of the Most High God, who proclaim to you the way of salvation.

04:13.893 --> 04:16.657
In this, she kept doing for many days.

04:17.558 --> 04:24.306
Paul, having become greatly annoyed, turned and said to the spirit, I command you in the name of Jesus Christ to come out of her.

04:24.450 --> 04:25.732
and it came out that very hour.

04:26.794 --> 04:34.285
But when her owners saw that their hope of gain was gone, they seized Paul and Silas and dragged them into the marketplace before the rulers.

04:35.026 --> 04:40.314
And when they had brought them to the magistrates, they said, these men are Jews and they are disturbing our city.

04:40.695 --> 04:45.763
They advocate customs that are not lawful for us as Romans to accept or practice.

04:45.783 --> 04:53.234
The crowd joined in attacking them and the magistrates tore their garments off them and gave order to beat them with rods.

04:53.378 --> 04:59.364
And when they had inflicted many blows upon them, they threw them into prison, ordering the jailer to keep them safely.

05:00.064 --> 05:04.929
Having received this order, he put them into the inner prison and fastened their feet in the stalks.

05:06.130 --> 05:12.437
About midnight, Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to God, and the prisoners were listening to them.

05:13.357 --> 05:17.802
And suddenly, there was a great earthquake so that the foundations of the prison were shaken.

05:17.842 --> 05:22.226
And immediately, all the doors were opened and everyone's bonds were unfastened.

05:22.754 --> 05:30.866
When the jailer woke and saw the prison doors were open, he drew his sword and was about to kill himself, supposing that the prisoners had escaped.

05:31.527 --> 05:35.393
But Paul cried with a loud voice, do not harm yourself, but we are all here.

05:35.433 --> 05:39.979
And the jailer called for lights and rushed in and trembling with fear.

05:40.480 --> 05:42.443
He fell down before Paul and Silas.

05:42.904 --> 05:47.110
Then he brought them out and said, sirs, what must I do to be saved?

05:47.911 --> 05:52.658
And they said, believe in the Lord Jesus and you will be saved, you and your household.

05:53.154 --> 05:56.659
when they spoke the word of the Lord to him and to all who were in his house.

05:57.500 --> 06:00.083
And he took them the same hour of the night and washed their wounds.

06:00.363 --> 06:01.585
And he was baptized at once.

06:01.705 --> 06:02.746
He and all his family.

06:03.447 --> 06:07.633
Then he brought them up into his house and set food before him, before them.

06:07.653 --> 06:12.619
And he rejoiced along with his entire household that he had believed in God.

06:13.721 --> 06:17.906
But when it was day, the magistrate sent the police saying, let those men go.

06:18.466 --> 06:25.813
And the jailer reported these words to Paul saying, the magistrates have sent to let you go, therefore come out now and go in peace.

06:26.474 --> 06:33.600
But Paul said to them, they have beaten us publicly, uncondemned men who are Roman citizens and have thrown us into prison.

06:34.141 --> 06:36.063
And do they now throw us out secretly?

06:36.103 --> 06:39.546
No, let them come themselves and take us out.

06:40.266 --> 06:45.752
The police reported these words to the magistrates and they were afraid when they heard that they were Roman citizens.

06:46.452 --> 06:48.274
So they came and apologized to them.

06:48.482 --> 06:50.465
And they took them out and asked them to leave the city.

06:51.085 --> 06:53.248
So they went out of the prison and visited Lydia.

06:53.568 --> 06:57.073
And when they had seen the brothers, they encouraged them and departed.

06:57.834 --> 06:58.675
This is God's word.

06:59.196 --> 06:59.696
Pray with me.

07:04.923 --> 07:16.978
God, we believe that it's your same Holy Spirit that's at work in Los Angeles today as he was in Philippi 2000 years ago.

07:17.218 --> 07:25.346
We believe that we're a part of this same story of the book of Acts and that you are the same God who is still changing lives and drawing people together.

07:25.386 --> 07:32.693
And so Lord, we pray that we would experience the same power of the gospel right here today in this place.

07:33.473 --> 07:36.136
God, we are desperate for you to move.

07:36.496 --> 07:47.026
We pray that you would reveal yourself, that you would open hearts, that you would draw us together and that you would make a genuine, powerful impact on this city.

07:47.490 --> 07:51.116
full of people who don't know you, but are longing for you.

07:52.038 --> 07:53.861
So God, show us yourself in this time.

07:53.901 --> 07:55.384
We pray this in Jesus' name.

07:55.864 --> 07:56.185
Amen.

07:56.946 --> 07:57.247
Amen.

07:58.349 --> 08:06.162
All right, so last week, we picked back up in Acts in the second missionary journey of the Apostle Paul.

08:06.274 --> 08:17.306
And if you remember a little bit from last week, they launch out on this missionary journey and it says that the spirit forbid them to go in one region and then close the door for them to go into another region.

08:17.866 --> 08:27.517
But then Paul had a vision from a man of Macedonia and he concluded that God was calling them to the city of Philippi to preach the gospel there.

08:27.537 --> 08:32.562
And so like I mentioned earlier, Philippi is a Roman city

08:33.026 --> 08:36.350
in ancient Greece, and there's zero believers there.

08:36.851 --> 08:43.760
But Paul and Barnabas are on a mission, on Christ's mission, to bring the good news of the gospel to everyone.

08:43.781 --> 08:49.608
And so they go to Philippi to start telling people about Jesus and to build a core team.

08:50.409 --> 08:51.190
And they travel.

08:51.211 --> 09:00.603
I mean, there's two days worth of sailing by ship over the Aegean Sea, and then they walk 10 miles to get to Philippi, and they get there.

09:01.945 --> 09:02.706
And what do you do?

09:02.882 --> 09:04.905
There's not one believer in the whole place.

09:05.586 --> 09:14.238
Well, what we do is in this story is we're introduced to three individuals who become the core team of this new church plant in Philippi.

09:14.859 --> 09:26.215
Three individuals who come together and what I wanna do is simply introduce them to you and then we'll talk about how a church can thrive in a pagan city, whether it's Philippi or Los Angeles.

09:26.696 --> 09:29.860
All right, so let me introduce these three core members to you.

09:29.880 --> 09:30.962
It starts off with

09:31.490 --> 09:36.658
Lydia and Lydia we meet in Acts 16 and we're told

09:37.314 --> 09:39.476
that Lydia is from Thyatira.

09:39.796 --> 09:42.458
Now, this is in the Roman province of Asia.

09:42.719 --> 09:45.481
It's a long ways away from Philippi, which is in Greece.

09:45.681 --> 09:48.243
So we learn early on that Lydia is mobile.

09:48.524 --> 09:49.625
She's independent.

09:50.005 --> 09:56.030
And as we learn next, she would have been wealthy because she was a seller of purple goods.

09:56.531 --> 10:03.236
So this is likely referring to clothing and purple dye was very expensive in the ancient world.

10:03.257 --> 10:07.300
So it would always be associated with wealth and luxury.

10:07.280 --> 10:10.523
is a high-end fashion designer.

10:10.744 --> 10:11.544
That's what she's doing.

10:11.584 --> 10:19.473
She's supplying the upper echelon of the people of Philippi with the clothes that they're wearing, with the things that they're putting in their homes.

10:19.793 --> 10:27.181
She's wealthy, she's independent, and not only is she selling expensive stuff, we know she's wealthy because she owns her own home.

10:27.541 --> 10:29.403
And this isn't even where she's from.

10:29.883 --> 10:31.985
She's an international traveler.

10:32.746 --> 10:36.370
And so Lydia is front diatira.

10:36.834 --> 10:41.553
cellar of purple goods, and they were told that she was a worshiper of God.

10:41.915 --> 10:47.538
Now what this means is that she wasn't a Jew, but she was worshipping the God of the Jews.

10:48.066 --> 11:03.221
So she's in this Greco-Roman context where everyone believes in all these different Greek and Roman gods, but she had this curiosity, something about her that she was drawn to the God of the Jews and she was learning and growing in these ways.

11:03.301 --> 11:05.904
And so Lydia is there in Philippi.

11:05.964 --> 11:15.954
And what happens is that Paul and Silas come to Philippi and normally what they do is they go to a city and they find the synagogue and they go there.

11:16.098 --> 11:18.641
But in Philippi, there's not even a synagogue.

11:18.661 --> 11:22.726
A synagogue would require 10 male Jews to have, they didn't even have that.

11:23.267 --> 11:28.794
So they go outside of the city by the river and there's some women who are getting together to pray.

11:29.715 --> 11:38.607
And Paul and Silas go up to these women by the river and begin talking with them and find out that they're worshiping the God of the Old Testament.

11:38.727 --> 11:44.274
And so they have a conversation and it says that the Lord

11:44.418 --> 11:46.500
Opened Lydia's heart.

11:46.981 --> 12:13.650
This is the key that she's searching but her heart had been closed closed and she hears the good news of Jesus proclaimed by Paul and Silas the Lord opens her heart and it says that she was baptized her and her whole household She's dipped into the water representing that she's dying to her old self She's rising from the grave united with the resurrected Jesus and then

12:14.114 --> 12:16.557
She immediately invites them to her house.

12:17.799 --> 12:19.821
She invites Paul and Silas into her home.

12:19.882 --> 12:20.943
So that's Lydia.

12:21.283 --> 12:24.347
She's the first Christian in Philippi.

12:25.709 --> 12:28.853
She's the first part of the core team of this church plant.

12:28.873 --> 12:32.798
Then we go on and the next person that we meet is a slave girl.

12:33.660 --> 12:38.546
This slave girl, we don't know much of her story, but we know that it would have been rough.

12:39.522 --> 12:50.195
This was a girl who had been sold into slavery, separated from her parents, from her family, lost any agency, power that she had over her own life.

12:50.976 --> 12:53.099
She's at the whim of her owners.

12:54.200 --> 12:58.826
And we're told that this slave girl had a spirit of divination.

12:59.266 --> 13:08.818
In the original language of Greek, and this is in Greece, in the original language of Greek, this literally says a spirit of a python.

13:09.474 --> 13:19.028
What that means is that the Greek God Apollo, there was a temple nearby for him, and they had snakes that would protect the temple.

13:19.048 --> 13:23.635
And they believed that Apollo would sometimes be embodied as a python.

13:24.056 --> 13:32.248
And so there were women who were seen as snakes protecting the temple of Apollo, and she would have been one of those women.

13:32.749 --> 13:35.333
So she had a spirit of a python.

13:35.373 --> 13:38.898
She's tormented by evil spirits within her.

13:39.394 --> 13:45.004
And then it says that she also, her owners had much gain from her fortune telling.

13:45.725 --> 13:51.275
So by these evil spirits, she has the power to predict the future.

13:52.417 --> 13:59.349
And she does this in such a way that people will come and pay large amounts for, but she's not getting that money.

14:00.051 --> 14:04.178
What we learn about this slave girl is that she's being exploited.

14:04.834 --> 14:06.617
She's owned by somebody else.

14:07.058 --> 14:11.085
They make her do this and then they take all the profits from her.

14:11.706 --> 14:13.409
She's been completely exploited.

14:13.449 --> 14:21.624
She has no agency or power in and of herself, but she's used by others, reduced as an object to make money for them.

14:22.666 --> 14:27.154
And so what happens is Paul and Silas are going back to the river.

14:27.810 --> 14:30.074
where they met Lydia at first.

14:30.434 --> 14:34.962
And as they're going, this slave girl comes and begins heckling them.

14:35.783 --> 14:38.047
These are servants of the Most High God.

14:38.748 --> 14:41.853
And it says she's yelling this at them and she does it on and on.

14:41.994 --> 14:47.443
It goes on for minutes and then hours and then days.

14:48.084 --> 14:49.426
She won't stop.

14:49.602 --> 14:57.842
This, Paul and Silas are being followed everywhere they go by this woman who's tormented by spirits and she's hackling them.

14:58.865 --> 15:02.674
And we're told that Paul is greatly annoyed.

15:03.138 --> 15:04.660
I mean, I love this.

15:05.021 --> 15:06.843
It shows the humanity of Paul.

15:07.184 --> 15:11.810
Like we imagine Paul everywhere he goes, like he's praying, he's walking in humility.

15:12.190 --> 15:15.775
Like Lord Jesus, like the picture that we get here is Paul's annoyed.

15:15.815 --> 15:20.221
Like, you know, when you're trying to focus and there's a mosquito and you're like, I'm not gonna just focus.

15:20.662 --> 15:24.067
The mosquito finally was like, you know, just start going after this mosquito.

15:24.387 --> 15:28.072
Like Paul's there on a mission to preach Jesus.

15:28.353 --> 15:29.394
He's got a heckler.

15:29.858 --> 15:34.105
This slave girl's following him around, yelling at him everywhere he goes.

15:34.365 --> 15:40.775
And finally, he gets so annoyed that he turns and says, in the name of Jesus, I command you to come out of her.

15:41.376 --> 15:42.778
And the spirit comes out of her.

15:43.800 --> 15:44.862
She's set free.

15:44.882 --> 15:50.290
It doesn't say explicitly that she's converted here, but

15:50.434 --> 15:55.901
She's gotta be, because her story is put right in the middle of two clear conversion stories.

15:56.602 --> 16:01.869
And this is someone who's being tormented by an evil spirit, and the spirit comes out, he's gone.

16:01.929 --> 16:05.614
And so here's a woman who was set free.

16:05.674 --> 16:10.401
She's been bound by demons, and she's set free.

16:11.082 --> 16:13.905
She walks away, a different person.

16:16.128 --> 16:17.330
But when

16:17.506 --> 16:19.969
this slave girl is set free.

16:20.029 --> 16:25.956
I'm sure it must have been a joyous occasion for her, but her owners were not happy about it at all.

16:27.277 --> 16:31.282
Because what happened is she's no longer has a spirit of divination.

16:31.302 --> 16:36.888
She's no longer a fortune teller predicting people's future based off of an evil power.

16:36.928 --> 16:41.874
And so what happened is that disrupted

16:41.954 --> 16:43.917
the finances of her owners.

16:44.518 --> 16:48.704
They lost their means of gain in this woman's ability.

16:49.225 --> 16:50.727
And so they were angry.

16:50.747 --> 16:55.695
It says that they seized Paul and Silas and they dragged them before the rulers.

16:55.715 --> 16:59.821
And they say, these Jews are disturbing our city.

17:00.241 --> 17:04.127
They're advocating customs that are not lawful for us as Romans.

17:04.167 --> 17:08.754
They're probably referring here to the proclamation that Caesar is Lord.

17:09.090 --> 17:12.358
and saying that our ultimate allegiance is political to Caesar.

17:12.378 --> 17:16.368
And these people say that Jesus is Lord, and that we should give ultimate allegiance to him.

17:16.408 --> 17:20.498
They're saying, these Jews, they're not like us.

17:20.834 --> 17:23.097
And they don't live the way that Romans live.

17:23.137 --> 17:26.221
They're disrupting everything in our city.

17:26.241 --> 17:30.627
And when they bring them before the rulers, the crowd gathers around.

17:30.988 --> 17:33.391
The crowd joins in attacking them.

17:33.411 --> 17:36.295
And eventually they strip them of their clothes.

17:36.596 --> 17:40.361
They beat them with rods and they throw them in prison.

17:41.983 --> 17:45.488
And so that's the second member of this core team.

17:45.568 --> 17:46.309
It's a slave girl.

17:46.329 --> 17:47.370
We've got Lydia.

17:47.631 --> 17:50.034
She's wealthy fashion designer.

17:50.274 --> 17:54.838
And then you've got the slave girl who's been exploited and tormented by demons.

17:55.959 --> 18:00.684
But that leads to the third member of this core team, and that is the Roman jailer.

18:01.525 --> 18:09.092
And a jailer in this situation probably would have been a former soldier.

18:09.492 --> 18:14.557
That's usually what they would have in their culture, is that they would have somebody who is a soldier and who no longer was.

18:14.957 --> 18:16.238
They were good at that kind of thing.

18:16.278 --> 18:17.620
They would become a jailer.

18:17.640 --> 18:20.082
They would oversee the jail.

18:20.226 --> 18:28.340
This Roman jailer would have been somebody who had lived through war and conquering and probably done horrific things.

18:28.380 --> 18:30.704
Tough guy, rough around the edges.

18:30.764 --> 18:33.268
And now he's a jailer.

18:33.288 --> 18:37.896
He's a Roman, believes in the Roman gods like everyone else does in Philippi.

18:37.956 --> 18:41.362
And so Paul and Silas are thrown into

18:41.762 --> 18:56.643
this prison, and it says the jailer puts them in the middle where they have no fresh air, no sunlight, anything like that, puts their feet in stocks, and it says that night, at about midnight, that what were Paul and Silas doing?

18:56.663 --> 18:59.827
They were praying and singing hymns to God.

19:00.569 --> 19:03.853
I mean, can we just pause and acknowledge how amazing this is?

19:04.334 --> 19:10.162
Like, I lock my keys in my car, and I'm like, Lord, you've abandoned me.

19:10.498 --> 19:12.720
I forget to record a show that I want to watch.

19:12.740 --> 19:14.622
And I'm like, God, why is life so hard?

19:15.543 --> 19:18.346
Like we question God over the littlest thing.

19:18.386 --> 19:19.887
Here's Paul and Silas.

19:20.147 --> 19:25.653
They've just gotten beaten with rods, thrown in prison for preaching the gospel.

19:25.933 --> 19:26.714
And what are they doing?

19:27.274 --> 19:28.035
They're singing.

19:28.075 --> 19:31.979
They're worshiping in the middle of the prison.

19:32.019 --> 19:35.883
And I want you to notice a little minor detail.

19:35.903 --> 19:39.186
It says, after midnight, Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to God.

19:39.298 --> 19:41.581
and the prisoners were listening to them.

19:42.682 --> 19:43.443
Can you imagine?

19:43.483 --> 19:49.330
They're in their praising God and these other prisoners are like, what is wrong with these guys?

19:50.171 --> 19:50.892
Who are they?

19:50.952 --> 19:56.659
Like they should be cursing their God and they're praising God?

19:57.460 --> 19:58.982
Like what's going on here?

19:59.322 --> 20:01.325
And the jailer must have heard him too.

20:02.166 --> 20:03.968
It's after midnight, it's silent.

20:04.869 --> 20:08.754
And yet Paul and Silas are crying out, praising God.

20:09.154 --> 20:11.396
that they get to join in the suffering of Christ.

20:11.736 --> 20:19.824
That they get to be a part of the beautiful work that God is doing of bringing His kingdom through service and sacrifice and suffering.

20:19.844 --> 20:21.486
They're praising God, the jailer hears.

20:21.846 --> 20:25.469
And then in the midst of that, an earthquake happens.

20:25.489 --> 20:29.273
The walls shake, the shackles fall away.

20:29.313 --> 20:33.517
And you can imagine that everyone in the prison, they look around like they can just leave.

20:33.577 --> 20:36.800
And then we're told that the jailer sees this.

20:37.661 --> 20:39.122
He realizes what's happened.

20:39.490 --> 20:42.455
And the jailer knows that if everybody gets out, then he hasn't done his job.

20:42.515 --> 20:43.396
He will lose his life.

20:44.638 --> 20:50.047
And so the jailer takes his sword and gets ready to plunge it into himself.

20:51.870 --> 20:54.034
And Paul cries out and he says, stop.

20:54.534 --> 20:55.115
We're all here.

20:55.155 --> 20:56.437
We're not going anywhere.

20:56.478 --> 21:00.524
And the jailer, I mean, he's so confused.

21:00.544 --> 21:01.125
He's shocked.

21:01.145 --> 21:02.828
He's heard these men singing all night.

21:03.609 --> 21:06.674
All of a sudden they have the chance to leave and they're not.

21:07.202 --> 21:09.626
And he goes to them and says, fear and trembling.

21:09.666 --> 21:12.971
And he says, what must I do to be saved?

21:14.113 --> 21:15.455
He sees what they have.

21:15.475 --> 21:18.621
He says, I want that what must I do to be saved?

21:18.661 --> 21:24.831
And Paul says, believe in the Lord Jesus and you will be saved you and your entire household.

21:25.953 --> 21:27.816
And we're told that the man believes.

21:29.098 --> 21:30.400
He believes in Jesus.

21:31.241 --> 21:32.443
He's baptized.

21:33.124 --> 21:34.226
And then you know, he does.

21:34.850 --> 21:37.213
He takes Paul and Silas to his house.

21:38.235 --> 21:42.160
He washes their wounds, and he serves them dinner.

21:43.142 --> 21:43.843
It's beautiful.

21:45.565 --> 21:56.501
And yeah, what's amazing about this is that they went to the house, they do the baptism, they have a meal, they get cleaned up, and then they went back to the prison.

21:58.864 --> 22:03.250
Because Paul and Silas, they didn't want this guy to lose his life.

22:04.162 --> 22:06.605
So they knew if they escaped, that it would be on him.

22:06.665 --> 22:09.750
So they literally go back to the prison.

22:09.770 --> 22:12.173
And I want you to think about this.

22:12.233 --> 22:13.855
I mean, it's an amazing story.

22:13.916 --> 22:16.479
And you can look at this story in different ways.

22:16.559 --> 22:20.364
At one level, you could hear this story and think, it's amazing and earthquake.

22:20.665 --> 22:23.088
God delivered Paul and Silas from prison.

22:23.128 --> 22:25.331
But that's not the point of the story.

22:25.371 --> 22:29.577
The point of the story is not God's physical deliverance of Paul and Silas.

22:29.958 --> 22:33.042
It's God's spiritual deliverance of the Roman jailer.

22:33.890 --> 22:36.674
I mean, imagine them sitting in that prison.

22:36.694 --> 22:39.037
Here's the question before this before they get released.

22:40.359 --> 22:42.422
Who is really free?

22:44.065 --> 22:46.608
Paul is suffering.

22:46.648 --> 22:49.632
He's in chains, but he's rejoicing.

22:50.353 --> 22:51.675
He's praising God.

22:51.715 --> 22:52.937
He's free.

22:52.997 --> 22:59.947
And yet the jailer, he's got the key that unlocks everything, but he's the one who's enslaved.

23:00.949 --> 23:01.970
This is a story.

23:02.594 --> 23:11.933
about how a Roman jailer who'd spent his life worshiping pagan gods, how he is set free by the grace of God.

23:13.437 --> 23:20.792
And so this is the core group of the church plant in Philippi, Lydia, the slave girl, and the Roman jailer.

23:21.574 --> 23:23.698
And I want you to

23:23.906 --> 23:28.158
get a feel for how radical it is of these three people coming together.

23:28.238 --> 23:31.708
This being the core group of a church plant, like nobody would choose this.

23:31.848 --> 23:35.157
So let's imagine these people as Angelenos, okay?

23:35.699 --> 23:38.326
So Lydia, she's the fashion designer.

23:38.366 --> 23:39.730
She lives in Beverly Hills.

23:39.842 --> 23:41.445
She's driving a nice car.

23:41.485 --> 23:47.715
She's wearing her Prada and her Saint Laurent and all the nice stuff.

23:47.735 --> 23:49.999
She's got all the high-end stuff.

23:50.019 --> 23:56.150
She's got her luxury fashion place on Melrose, like that's Lydia, okay?

23:56.951 --> 23:58.173
And then there's the slave girl.

23:59.014 --> 24:05.906
Maybe she's like a young homeless girl in downtown who was forced to into prostitution.

24:06.242 --> 24:07.485
and has lost everything.

24:07.506 --> 24:10.574
She's destitute, and she's tormented by demons.

24:11.737 --> 24:12.720
And then there's the jailer.

24:12.760 --> 24:16.651
Maybe I think of a retired police officer in North Hollywood.

24:17.293 --> 24:21.906
He's done his time, but he needs to make a little extra money, so he's a security guard at night.

24:22.690 --> 24:34.368
So imagine this, three very different people, a successful fashion entrepreneur in Beverly Hills, a young woman trapped in exploitation in downtown LA, a retired officer working security in the valley.

24:34.789 --> 24:36.412
They would never be in the same room.

24:36.712 --> 24:46.067
They don't share the same zip code, friend groups, social media feeds, and yet in Act 16, those kinds of people are in the same church.

24:47.028 --> 24:48.050
And that's the point.

24:48.770 --> 24:51.314
The gospel doesn't just save individuals.

24:51.655 --> 24:56.002
It creates a community that would never assemble naturally.

24:56.984 --> 24:58.686
That's what happens in Philippi.

24:58.706 --> 25:03.955
And so what I want you to see is this isn't just a story of three amazing conversions.

25:04.716 --> 25:10.506
This is three people who meet Jesus and then who are formed into a community that's called a church.

25:11.427 --> 25:13.010
And so in verse 40, the very last

25:13.538 --> 25:14.980
verse of this chapter.

25:15.641 --> 25:25.613
It says that Paul and Silas, that when they do leave prison, they go back to Lydia's house and it says that they see the brothers and sisters.

25:26.514 --> 25:26.995
So what do you have?

25:27.015 --> 25:34.504
You have these three random people in this story who most likely didn't even know each other, didn't cross paths from very different walks of life.

25:34.824 --> 25:39.390
And yet they all meet Jesus and now they're family, brothers and sisters.

25:40.371 --> 25:42.834
And here's the thing, this is the core group of this church plant.

25:43.394 --> 25:48.981
But this church would go on and grow and thrive.

25:49.021 --> 25:55.168
And we know that because Paul would write a letter to this church about 10 to 12 years later.

25:55.188 --> 25:56.570
And we have it in our Bible.

25:56.610 --> 25:59.913
It's called the book of Philippians to the church.

26:00.254 --> 26:02.617
It's a letter to the church in Philippi.

26:03.538 --> 26:06.141
And so this is the church plant in Philippi.

26:06.201 --> 26:10.546
That's the core group, these three individuals.

26:10.658 --> 26:13.220
that goes on to be a thriving church.

26:13.861 --> 26:15.903
And so what can we learn from this?

26:17.144 --> 26:25.552
I wanna talk about how a church can thrive in a pagan city and talk about, share five truths that we learn from this story about that.

26:26.193 --> 26:28.716
So here's the first, how can a church thrive in a pagan city?

26:29.116 --> 26:32.499
We have to know that the gospel grows the church.

26:33.460 --> 26:39.506
And so when you look at this story, Paul and Silas planting the church, it's not their methods that do this.

26:39.906 --> 26:44.714
Like it wasn't that Paul was so persuasive and intelligent with Lydia.

26:44.995 --> 26:47.159
It says that the Lord opened her heart.

26:48.240 --> 26:51.907
I mean, with the slave girl, it wasn't that Paul was like so powerful.

26:52.107 --> 26:52.949
He was annoyed.

26:53.009 --> 26:55.753
And yet God worked through him.

26:55.814 --> 27:03.467
That woman encountered the power of the Holy Spirit that was stronger than any demon that had ever oppressed her.

27:04.108 --> 27:05.330
And even with the jailer,

27:05.922 --> 27:07.444
Paul didn't make an earthquake happen.

27:07.764 --> 27:09.466
God's the one who shook the prison.

27:09.706 --> 27:13.891
And it was the jailer's suffering that led him to ask, what must I do to be saved?

27:15.112 --> 27:20.459
So it's not, it's not their methods that make this church grow and become what it is.

27:20.479 --> 27:30.450
I mean, imagine Paul, like at a first century church planting conference and, and all these young church planners are coming up to him and they're like, Paul,

27:30.850 --> 27:32.492
Man, I heard about the church in Philippi.

27:32.532 --> 27:33.093
Amazing.

27:33.113 --> 27:34.775
Like, I want to plant a church.

27:35.216 --> 27:37.039
Like the church in Philippi, what do I got to do?

27:37.459 --> 27:38.320
Give me the strategies.

27:38.340 --> 27:39.322
You can't tell me how to preach.

27:39.362 --> 27:40.103
Give me the mechanisms.

27:40.363 --> 27:41.244
Like, what do I do?

27:41.265 --> 27:45.971
I just imagine the apostle Paul saying, well, here's what you do.

27:46.532 --> 27:47.774
You get heckled by a demon.

27:48.134 --> 27:52.360
You get beaten by officers, thrown in jail, and then make an earthquake happen.

27:52.580 --> 27:53.401
Works every time.

27:54.423 --> 27:55.544
It'll be a great church.

27:56.946 --> 27:57.647
No, here's the thing.

27:57.667 --> 27:59.570
We actually know exactly.

27:59.746 --> 28:20.397
how Paul looked back on this experience in Acts 16, because when Paul wrote his letter to the church in Philippi, after reflecting on all that for 10, 12 years, he says this to them in Philippians 1, 6, he said, I'm sure of this, that he who began a good work in you will bring it to completion at the day of Jesus Christ.

28:22.120 --> 28:24.744
He who began a good work in you, did you catch that?

28:24.784 --> 28:28.690
Paul's saying, I didn't start the church in Philippi,

28:28.962 --> 28:31.206
I didn't begin that work.

28:31.226 --> 28:33.770
It wasn't me and Silas that did great things.

28:34.591 --> 28:35.913
God planted that church.

28:36.654 --> 28:37.676
That's God's church.

28:38.136 --> 28:40.821
God began that work in that church.

28:41.201 --> 28:45.067
And he's the one that's going to grow it, that's going to sustain it.

28:45.468 --> 28:48.813
It's going to use it to shine his light in the Roman Empire.

28:49.214 --> 28:51.077
God's the one who did that.

28:52.259 --> 28:54.482
And so the gospel is what grows the church.

28:55.074 --> 28:56.456
Jesus builds the church.

28:56.856 --> 28:58.338
It's his death and resurrection.

28:58.378 --> 29:01.201
That's the power of salvation to the Jew and to the Gentile.

29:01.661 --> 29:04.384
The Holy Spirit is the one who brings real change.

29:04.725 --> 29:07.928
The father adopts us into a new family.

29:07.968 --> 29:11.172
The gospel is what grows the church.

29:11.933 --> 29:15.376
So let's apply this to our church right here in Los Angeles.

29:15.577 --> 29:18.260
How can we thrive as a church in a pagan city?

29:18.300 --> 29:20.402
Well, the danger is

29:21.122 --> 29:25.907
when we think that that will happen by relying on mechanisms, formulas, and ministry strategies.

29:26.828 --> 29:36.257
All you gotta do to plant a thriving church in Los Angeles is get a dynamic preacher, really talented worship band, slick Instagram profile, and a cool venue.

29:36.477 --> 29:37.218
Then we'll grow.

29:37.278 --> 29:38.739
It'll take off.

29:39.140 --> 29:40.301
It'll be amazing.

29:40.361 --> 29:47.928
Listen, that's trying to manufacture something by human strength that can only truly be created by the power of the Spirit.

29:48.929 --> 29:49.810
I'll tell you this.

29:50.210 --> 29:54.676
The only reason that we are here today as a church is because of the grace of God.

29:55.757 --> 29:58.561
He began the good work that has happened here.

29:58.601 --> 30:01.705
It's his grace that moves us forward.

30:02.145 --> 30:10.335
The only reason we will continue to grow and be a gospel presence in this city is because of the grace of God and the power of the gospel.

30:11.357 --> 30:18.706
And you know, as a pastor who's been here in LA now for 13 years, I get church planners coming to me and saying, what do I do?

30:18.978 --> 30:23.846
I want to play a church like Reality LA, and we want to be in the heart of the city and proclaiming the gospel.

30:24.928 --> 30:26.291
I'll share principles with them.

30:26.351 --> 30:37.250
I'll talk with them about the importance of godly character and leadership and the need to preach the word and how you have to make disciples and build everything in your church around making disciples.

30:37.290 --> 30:42.098
But at the end of the day, I say to these planters, I say, it's the power of the gospel.

30:42.274 --> 30:46.840
Ministry is stewardship, being faithful with what God is doing.

30:46.860 --> 30:49.323
And so the honestly, the best thing that you can do is pray.

30:49.403 --> 30:57.653
Just cry out that God would move, that he would do it again, that he would reveal himself, that he would transform people.

30:57.693 --> 31:01.357
That's what grows the church.

31:02.278 --> 31:05.202
And look, I'm not down against,

31:05.602 --> 31:08.827
like mechanisms or ministry strategies, those are great.

31:09.928 --> 31:12.252
I'm not saying that systems and structures don't matter.

31:13.373 --> 31:17.800
I like to think about it like this, like a trellis and a vine.

31:18.481 --> 31:27.935
So if you go up to Napa Valley and you look out over a vineyard, what you'll see is you'll see lots of vines with grapes growing on them.

31:27.955 --> 31:33.583
It's beautiful, but you'll notice that they're upon trellises, these wood frames that are built.

31:34.444 --> 31:35.506
And so with

31:35.650 --> 31:37.533
a vineyard, it's about the vine.

31:37.573 --> 31:39.916
The vine is what produces the fruit.

31:40.938 --> 31:49.690
But you need a trellis, which is the framework, to make sure that the vine is growing in the right way, not getting choked out by weeds and whatnot.

31:50.391 --> 31:55.118
And so when we talk about the church, it's about the vine.

31:55.158 --> 32:03.410
It's about life in Christ, abiding in Him, the ministry of disciples, making disciples, seeing people,

32:03.490 --> 32:10.791
who don't know Jesus, become followers of Jesus and getting connected in community and sent out a salt and light in the city.

32:10.811 --> 32:11.994
That's what it's about.

32:12.877 --> 32:14.401
But we need some trellis.

32:15.143 --> 32:18.834
We need some structure to make sure that that's happening well.

32:18.946 --> 32:26.554
We need to make sure that we have staff that is making sure that all the finances that we have are dealt with in a way that's above reproach.

32:27.275 --> 32:32.761
We need communication so people can understand what's going on and how to be involved in the right way.

32:32.821 --> 32:42.591
We need people who are planning ministry programs and events and making sure that they're well coordinated so that people can get to them and so they can function well.

32:43.032 --> 32:45.074
We need all of that, but here's the thing.

32:45.666 --> 32:51.313
Like nobody goes to the vineyard and says, what a beautiful trellis.

32:52.414 --> 32:53.496
Like that's amazing.

32:54.036 --> 33:02.066
And if there were no vine, if all the vine died and it was just dust and nobody would go and celebrate the trellis, it's not about the trellis.

33:03.067 --> 33:04.790
So we need to have healthy structures.

33:05.631 --> 33:06.391
We need all of that.

33:06.452 --> 33:14.962
Our staff does an amazing job, pouring, sacrificially, working so hard so that we have this so that you all can be equipped

33:15.202 --> 33:16.724
to do the work of ministry.

33:16.764 --> 33:19.827
So we need all of that, but it's not about the trellis.

33:20.687 --> 33:29.436
It's about Jesus growing the church and us being united to him and proclaiming him and witnessing to him in word and deed in our lives.

33:30.717 --> 33:35.983
And I'll tell you this, I want to experience more of the power of the gospel in our city so bad.

33:37.484 --> 33:43.570
Los Angeles is filled with litias and slave girls and Roman jailers.

33:44.290 --> 33:46.633
And only the gospel can transform them.

33:47.414 --> 33:51.658
Only the gospel can reconcile them to God and bring them into a new family.

33:53.100 --> 33:55.082
So how can a church thrive in a pagan city?

33:55.102 --> 33:58.466
Well, we've got to know first that the gospel grows the church.

33:58.486 --> 34:03.351
Second, we've got to know that the gospel is for all people, all people.

34:03.992 --> 34:09.138
And some of us have a stereotype in our minds of who might become a Christian.

34:09.986 --> 34:19.216
When you think of like somebody who you wanna pray for, that they might become a Christian, you might think of a person, they dress a certain way, they talk a certain way, they look a certain way.

34:19.537 --> 34:22.780
That's the kind of person who might become a Christian.

34:23.000 --> 34:27.726
And you probably have a stereotype of the kind of person who would never become a Christian.

34:28.667 --> 34:39.058
Well, this passage makes clear that the gospel is for all people, people of different genders, ethnicities, classes, spiritual backgrounds.

34:39.362 --> 34:46.250
And I'll tell you this, these three people who made the core group of the church plan in Philippi, they could not be more different from one another.

34:47.011 --> 34:47.972
In fact, let me show you this.

34:47.992 --> 34:49.674
Look at this chart that I have here.

34:49.714 --> 34:54.599
And look at how different these three figures are in every way.

34:54.619 --> 35:04.711
I mean, you've got ethnically, so Lydia is Asian, the slave girl is most likely Greek and the jailer is a Roman.

35:05.552 --> 35:07.634
And then you've got economically,

35:07.810 --> 35:09.313
Lydia is wealthy.

35:09.353 --> 35:13.381
The slave girl is poor and the jailer is middle class.

35:14.202 --> 35:22.238
And then spiritually, Lydia was seeking the slave girl was opposed and the jailer was indifferent.

35:23.220 --> 35:27.327
That they couldn't be more different people from different types of backgrounds.

35:28.049 --> 35:28.690
And yet,

35:28.994 --> 35:34.544
The gospel crosses ethnic lines, economic lines, and spiritual starting points.

35:34.965 --> 35:37.850
This is the core group of the church plant in Philippi.

35:38.090 --> 35:39.332
The gospel's for everyone.

35:39.392 --> 35:40.074
It's amazing.

35:41.035 --> 35:44.502
And I tell you what, there would have definitely been some tension.

35:44.542 --> 35:48.028
There would have been some messiness in this core group and in this church plant.

35:48.689 --> 35:53.778
Because all these different differences that they had, they would have brought in different personalities.

35:53.890 --> 36:01.962
different political understandings, different experiences, different levels of maturity, emotionally, mentally.

36:03.063 --> 36:07.570
In every sense, it would have been messy and difficult, and yet it was beautiful.

36:07.610 --> 36:09.352
It's the gospel bringing these people together.

36:10.213 --> 36:11.535
And so what would it look like?

36:11.635 --> 36:13.198
What would this look like in Los Angeles?

36:14.139 --> 36:18.145
Well, at one level, we're already experiencing this.

36:18.405 --> 36:21.970
So we literally have fashion designers in our church,

36:22.530 --> 36:25.174
We have people in our church who used to be fortune tellers.

36:25.955 --> 36:27.778
And we have a jailer in our church.

36:28.359 --> 36:29.200
So we've got this.

36:30.983 --> 36:37.613
And beyond that, seriously, we have people from different ethnic backgrounds, socioeconomic backgrounds and spiritual backgrounds.

36:38.154 --> 36:41.719
And yet we've been transformed by Jesus and are a part of the same family.

36:42.360 --> 36:44.123
God is still working in these ways.

36:44.203 --> 36:45.105
He's the same God.

36:45.125 --> 36:46.447
We're a part of the same story.

36:47.148 --> 36:48.690
But we want to see more of this.

36:48.930 --> 36:54.919
We want to see people from all walks of life encountering Christ and being brought into his family.

36:55.800 --> 36:59.806
So whoever it is that you might assume they would never become a Christian or the Gospels not for them.

36:59.846 --> 37:10.161
Those are exactly the people that you need to start praying for and that you need to build relationships with and show the love of Christ to and show the Gospel with them.

37:11.363 --> 37:13.426
So the Gospels for all people

37:13.538 --> 37:16.702
But the gospel doesn't just reach people from various backgrounds.

37:16.782 --> 37:21.127
Next, we learn that the gospel reaches different people in different ways.

37:22.189 --> 37:23.030
This is incredible.

37:23.731 --> 37:28.917
So think about what happens with these three different individuals who make up this core team.

37:29.718 --> 37:32.862
So Lydia is converted through words.

37:33.643 --> 37:42.514
So it's a conversation with Paul and Silas where they're engaging with things intellectually and they're going back and forth and the Lord opens her heart and she becomes a Christian.

37:42.914 --> 37:44.877
So Lydia was converted with words.

37:45.678 --> 37:47.481
For the slave girl, it was power.

37:48.262 --> 37:56.614
She encountered a power in the Holy Spirit that was far beyond the power of any demon that had tormented her.

37:57.435 --> 38:00.620
So for her, it was power for Lydia, it's words for the slave girl's power.

38:00.880 --> 38:03.945
And for the jailer, he encountered the gospel through suffering.

38:05.066 --> 38:07.730
So his world shakes literally.

38:08.258 --> 38:14.006
He finds himself in despair and he's at the point of getting ready to take his own life.

38:14.928 --> 38:16.250
And those are the circumstances.

38:16.350 --> 38:19.915
It leads him to trusting in Christ and becoming a Christian.

38:21.137 --> 38:26.905
And so we need to recognize that the gospel is powerful and will reach different people in different ways.

38:27.887 --> 38:35.698
And sometimes when we think of evangelism, I think we might be tempted to think only about like Lydia's situation words.

38:35.938 --> 38:40.943
like sitting down, having a conversation with someone, explaining the gospel to them, that's important.

38:41.104 --> 38:44.127
And the proclamation of the good news is essential.

38:44.928 --> 38:56.240
But we also need to be aware that people are going to become Christians through power encounters, through healing, through being delivered, through radical experiences with God.

38:56.260 --> 38:57.401
And we need to pray for that.

38:57.802 --> 39:05.650
People are also going to become Christians through suffering, that they are gonna get to a place where their world is shaken,

39:06.370 --> 39:09.334
where they don't know where else to look, and they look to God.

39:09.955 --> 39:12.179
And we need to be there to proclaim the gospel.

39:12.779 --> 39:18.107
And look, that's not taking advantage of someone when they're suffering, of telling them about Jesus.

39:18.388 --> 39:21.653
It's bringing a real remedy to real brokenness.

39:22.654 --> 39:27.501
Often times it's in suffering where we realize that we're really not in control of our own lives.

39:28.222 --> 39:30.686
We really aren't the master of our own destiny.

39:31.627 --> 39:36.114
And where we, it's in those moments of suffering, loss, and pain,

39:36.386 --> 39:42.255
where we look to God who really is in control, who is sovereign, who is good, and who loves us.

39:42.736 --> 39:45.240
So the gospel reaches different people in different ways.

39:46.562 --> 39:51.390
The fourth truth that we learn from this story is that the gospel makes strangers family.

39:52.111 --> 39:55.396
So like I said, this isn't just a story of three individuals.

39:56.037 --> 40:01.586
It's the beginning of a new community in the city of Philippi.

40:01.762 --> 40:03.484
They become brothers and sisters.

40:03.524 --> 40:04.626
That's how the story ends.

40:05.106 --> 40:08.991
Paul visits them, sees the brothers and sisters in the church.

40:09.051 --> 40:12.235
So the gospel takes people who are strangers and makes them families.

40:13.376 --> 40:14.938
And you see this.

40:14.978 --> 40:20.806
I mean, how this church goes on and becomes a church family that's established.

40:21.386 --> 40:27.474
So when Paul writes the letter to the church in Philippi, a decade later, he says this.

40:27.618 --> 40:32.824
to all the saints in Christ Jesus who are at Philippi with the overseers and the deacons.

40:33.946 --> 40:34.587
That's amazing.

40:34.607 --> 40:37.770
I mean, 10 years later, they've got established leadership structures.

40:38.972 --> 40:39.352
Who knows?

40:39.433 --> 40:42.456
Maybe some of these three were some of those overseers and deacons.

40:43.317 --> 40:44.939
And he says, you're saints.

40:45.780 --> 40:47.102
You're not a slave girl.

40:47.142 --> 40:47.843
You're a saint.

40:47.903 --> 40:49.104
You're not a fashion designer.

40:49.124 --> 40:49.625
You're a saint.

40:49.645 --> 40:50.827
You're not a jailer.

40:51.047 --> 40:51.768
You're a saint.

40:51.788 --> 40:54.872
You've been made holy by Jesus Christ.

40:55.913 --> 40:56.914
And then he says to them,

40:57.442 --> 41:03.752
in this letter in verse three through five, he says, I thank my God, and all my remembrance of you, he's reflecting back on them.

41:03.792 --> 41:09.020
And he says, because of your partnership in the gospel, that word partnership is coin ania.

41:09.040 --> 41:15.369
It means fellowship, it's talking about shared life, shared mission, shared hope in Christ.

41:16.451 --> 41:23.762
And so it's the power of the gospel that's taken these strangers from different backgrounds and made them family.

41:24.034 --> 41:28.880
It's one of the reasons that you see this radical hospitality in this chapter.

41:28.900 --> 41:32.424
I mean, did you notice that Lydia opens her heart?

41:33.144 --> 41:36.188
Actually, God opens her heart and then she opens her home.

41:36.949 --> 41:38.150
She invites them into her home right away.

41:38.210 --> 41:40.193
The gospel makes us hospitable.

41:40.633 --> 41:41.935
Did you catch that with the jailer?

41:41.955 --> 41:46.340
That as soon as he believes in Jesus and trusts in him, what does he do?

41:46.840 --> 41:51.986
He washes them of their wounds, invites them into his home, and makes him dinner.

41:52.642 --> 42:03.934
The gospel makes us hospitable because we are a people who have been welcomed in by Jesus and therefore want to welcome others to say there's a place at the table for you.

42:05.175 --> 42:06.837
So the gospel makes strangers family.

42:06.857 --> 42:12.062
And then lastly, we learned from this passage that the gospel disrupts the order of the city.

42:13.243 --> 42:20.050
We need to hear this because there's a temptation to believe that the gospel is private and belongs only in the realm of personal spirituality.

42:20.354 --> 42:27.165
And then our society reinforces this, telling people, look, you can believe whatever you want as long as you keep your religious beliefs to yourself.

42:28.266 --> 42:34.456
But passages like this remind us that the power of the gospel cannot be limited to personal spirituality.

42:35.137 --> 42:39.744
The gospel impacts all of life and speaks not only to the heart, but to the public sphere.

42:40.606 --> 42:48.658
The kingdom is not a picture of your best life now, but a vision of the world reordered around the powerful love of God.

42:49.250 --> 42:50.892
Think about what happens in Acts 16.

42:51.933 --> 42:54.076
This slave girl was being tormented by demons.

42:54.456 --> 42:57.640
She was also being exploited by her owners.

42:58.681 --> 43:06.871
And when she is set free, it upsets the owners because it impacted them financially.

43:06.911 --> 43:07.932
Then what do they do?

43:08.172 --> 43:13.298
They go bring in government officials right after that and it disrupts the whole order of the city.

43:14.210 --> 43:20.482
And you see this throughout the gospel or throughout the book of Acts, Paul's not trying to go and disrupt cities.

43:20.542 --> 43:26.854
He's going and preaching the gospel, but it brings disruption socially, economically, politically, culturally.

43:26.874 --> 43:33.407
I mean, can you imagine if so many people in Los Angeles got saved at the porn industry shutdown?

43:34.149 --> 43:34.930
Can you imagine?

43:35.554 --> 43:39.620
If porn stars became followers of Jesus and said, I'm not doing this anymore.

43:40.061 --> 43:46.992
If the videographers and the sound technicians and the producers, they said, man, I believe these people are made in the image of God.

43:47.032 --> 43:51.018
I will not reduce them to a sexual object any longer.

43:51.278 --> 43:52.100
What if that happened?

43:52.360 --> 43:54.023
And the porn industry shut down.

43:54.083 --> 44:00.112
What if so many people in Los Angeles became Christians that fentanyl distribution dried up?

44:00.513 --> 44:04.018
Because drug dealers were getting saved and say, I'm not doing this anymore.

44:04.226 --> 44:14.798
Can you imagine if so many people in Los Angeles met Jesus that plastic surgery clinics saw fewer clients because people actually believed that they were fearfully and wonderfully made?

44:15.599 --> 44:30.315
Can you imagine if so many people in Los Angeles were transformed by the grace of Jesus that all the kids in Los Angeles foster care system got fostered or got adopted because they know that we've been adopted into the family of God and we want to be into an adoptive people?

44:30.375 --> 44:32.658
These are things that could happen.

44:33.282 --> 44:38.249
And I know, I know that some of you are saying that sounds great, but that would never actually happen.

44:39.211 --> 44:47.844
You know, that's probably what people said in the first few centuries in the Roman Empire, when it was a common practice to throw unwanted babies in the dump.

44:48.625 --> 44:50.467
It's what they used to do in the Roman Empire.

44:50.848 --> 44:54.994
And usually, if it wasn't a son, they wanted a son.

44:55.054 --> 44:59.501
And if they had a daughter, they might throw her in the dump and let the baby die.

44:59.781 --> 45:00.783
But you know what Christians did?

45:00.823 --> 45:03.026
They started going into the dumps.

45:03.394 --> 45:07.159
and pulling out the babies and taking care of them, starting orphanages.

45:07.679 --> 45:12.526
And they did this so much that eventually that practice, people stopped, changed the Roman Empire.

45:12.546 --> 45:19.034
You know, people probably would have said that would never actually happen about the abolition of the slave trade in Britain.

45:20.155 --> 45:28.466
And yet there were Christians who believed in the gospel, who saw the social implications of it, people like William Wilberforce and a group called the Clapham sect,

45:28.674 --> 45:34.643
that stood up for the dignity of all people, and it did lead to the abolition of the slave trade in Britain.

45:35.644 --> 45:41.894
People, you know, in America, in the South, probably would have said segregation will never be over with.

45:42.615 --> 45:54.913
And yet there were Christians, like Martin Luther King Jr. and Fred Shuttlesworth, and many others who believed that all people are made in the image of God and saw the implications of the gospel in all of life, who stood up and genuine change happened.

45:55.594 --> 45:58.418
And so we think, yeah, we can praise God for that.

45:59.426 --> 46:09.821
We think that industries are immovable, but Rome thought that infanticide was immovable.

46:10.342 --> 46:13.307
Britain thought the slave trade was an economic necessity.

46:13.547 --> 46:15.630
The South thought segregation was permanent.

46:16.071 --> 46:23.983
And yet, when the gospel takes root deeply enough in a people, it doesn't just save individuals, it rearranges public life.

46:25.084 --> 46:26.526
That's what we see in Philippi.

46:26.566 --> 46:29.010
That's what we can see in Los Angeles.

46:32.642 --> 46:38.591
And so the gospel transforms individuals, brings them together as a church, and it impacts the whole city.

46:38.611 --> 46:42.978
And honestly, that's why we're here as a church in Los Angeles.

46:43.839 --> 46:46.423
And by God's grace, we've been planted in the city.

46:47.064 --> 46:52.773
And we want to thrive, we want to bear fruit, we want to spread the seeds of the gospel and pray that the Lord would move.

46:54.215 --> 47:00.745
And I want us to close by going back to the question that the jailer asked in his low moment.

47:00.765 --> 47:01.426
He said,

47:01.506 --> 47:03.289
What must I do to be saved?"

47:04.230 --> 47:09.598
You know, people may not word it exactly like that, but that's the same question that people in Los Angeles are asking.

47:10.660 --> 47:12.222
Everyone's longing for salvation.

47:12.262 --> 47:19.253
We just look to functional saviors like our career or our reputation or money or ultimately ourselves.

47:19.333 --> 47:21.616
People are looking to be saved.

47:22.397 --> 47:25.241
And the jailer asks, what must I do to be saved?

47:25.302 --> 47:28.306
And how do you think people would answer that question?

47:28.930 --> 47:34.298
People in Los Angeles would probably say, well, I would guess that Paul would say, you gotta get your act together.

47:35.119 --> 47:38.323
You gotta stop doing that thing that you keep doing that you know is wrong.

47:39.024 --> 47:42.549
You gotta go back and make up for every wrong thing that you've done in life.

47:42.749 --> 47:44.732
You gotta work your way to God.

47:44.752 --> 47:49.599
That's what people would naturally think the answer to this question, what must I do to be saved is?

47:50.060 --> 47:52.703
Well, Paul says, when the jailer says, what must I do to be saved?

47:52.743 --> 47:55.848
He simply says, believe in the Lord Jesus and you will be saved.

47:56.749 --> 47:57.490
Here's the key.

47:58.050 --> 48:00.392
It's not, you don't have to do anything.

48:00.552 --> 48:04.176
In fact, it's the wrong question, what must I do to be saved?

48:04.596 --> 48:05.837
It's nothing that you do.

48:05.877 --> 48:08.960
It's believing in what Jesus has done for you.

48:09.000 --> 48:13.745
And what that is, is that He died on the cross for your sins.

48:14.426 --> 48:16.247
That's how you can live with freedom.

48:16.267 --> 48:23.594
That's how you can live with no guilt and no shame because Christ died for your sins so that you can be forgiven.

48:23.614 --> 48:25.876
And what else did He do for you?

48:25.936 --> 48:27.538
He rose from the grave.

48:28.002 --> 48:34.129
That's why you can live a new life, not on your own strength, but by the resurrection power of Jesus Christ.

48:35.271 --> 48:38.434
Believe in the Lord Jesus and you will be saved.

48:38.755 --> 48:42.239
Believe, follow him and get baptized.

48:43.040 --> 48:45.002
We're gonna do baptisms on Easter coming up.

48:45.423 --> 48:46.464
Some of you are in that place.

48:46.504 --> 48:49.167
Maybe today you're ready to believe or you have believed.

48:49.607 --> 48:50.328
Get baptized.

48:50.348 --> 48:51.249
That's what Lydia does.

48:51.289 --> 48:52.251
That's what the jailer does.

48:52.571 --> 48:55.154
They believe and they are baptized.

48:56.002 --> 48:57.203
I just want to close with this.

48:57.244 --> 49:03.171
I've referenced already how this church was dear to Paul's heart.

49:03.191 --> 49:05.073
He followed up with them.

49:05.093 --> 49:07.576
He wrote another letter to them.

49:07.616 --> 49:15.026
And in that letter, a decade later, he just comes back to the same basic truths.

49:15.847 --> 49:21.714
He wants to keep calling them back to what saved them, the good news of Jesus, and for them to know that there's nothing better.

49:21.986 --> 49:22.787
the knowing him.

49:22.827 --> 49:25.690
Here's what he said to them in Philippians three verse eight.

49:25.711 --> 49:31.417
He says, indeed, I count everything is lost because of the surpassing worth of knowing Christ Jesus, my Lord.

49:31.437 --> 49:51.762
For his sake, I have suffered the loss of all things and count them as rubbish in order that I may gain Christ and be found in him, not having a righteousness of my own, but that comes from the law, but that which comes through faith and Christ, the righteousness from God that depends on faith, that I may know him.

49:52.098 --> 50:01.731
and the power of his resurrection, and may share his sufferings, becoming like him in his death, that by any means possible, I may attain the resurrection from the dead.

50:02.432 --> 50:04.175
That was their hope from beginning to end.

50:04.215 --> 50:13.668
That's our hope from the beginning to the end, to believe that Jesus is Lord, that he died and that he rose, and that nothing compares to knowing him.

50:14.129 --> 50:14.609
Pray with me.

50:15.771 --> 50:20.978
God, we thank you so much for the incredible work that you did in the city of Philippi.

50:21.922 --> 50:25.246
And Lord, we thank You that You've been doing that work in cities all over the world.

50:25.266 --> 50:26.867
You've done it here in Los Angeles.

50:27.488 --> 50:29.971
And God, we just want to see more of that.

50:30.691 --> 50:42.844
We want to see not only our church, but other churches in this city thriving, where people are being encountered by Jesus and they're coming from all walks of life, but they're being made family in Christ.

50:43.645 --> 50:48.050
And so God, help us to be faithful stewards, to be,

50:48.130 --> 50:53.417
deliberate and diligent about making disciples and having healthy structures and all of that.

50:54.378 --> 50:57.142
But God more than anything, we pray that your spirit would move.

50:58.204 --> 51:00.347
Pray that your son Jesus would build his church.

51:01.168 --> 51:02.890
And Lord, we will give you all the glory for that.

51:03.110 --> 51:04.352
We pray this in your son's name.

51:04.793 --> 51:05.093
Amen.

51:06.034 --> 51:06.875
Thank you for listening.

51:07.476 --> 51:11.762
For more audio and video content, please visit realityla.com.

